### 8. Network Admission of AI Agent Instances & Scope-Down Access Control
* **Presenter**: Chao Zhou
* **Slides**: 
  * [08 Use Cases and Requirements for Network Admission of AI Agent Instances](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-anima-use-cases-and-requirements-for-network-admission-of-ai-agent-instances-01)
  * [09 Campus Agent Identification and Scope-Down Access Control](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-anima-campus-agent-identification-and-scope-down-access-control-02)
* **Key Details**:
  * **Network Admission**: Standard network firewalls cannot differentiate between distinct AI agents running on the same host or sharing the same IP address. Traditional authentication occurs too late in the application layer. Chao proposed a "verifiable agent binding" model where agent instances and cryptographic evidence are bound together, validated by a Network Admission Function, and enforced at Network Enforcement Points.
  * **Scope-Down Access Control**: Since AI agents dynamically invoke different services and tools, static privileges are too broad. Chao proposed "scope-down access control," which calculates the mathematical intersection of the agent's baseline privileges and its current task intent, ensuring the network only permits the minimum access required for the active task.

